      "verdict": "CONFIRMED",
      "reasoning": "Each equality between a cell in the first rectangle and the corresponding cell in the second rectangle imposes a constraint that merges two cells into one equivalence class. When the rectangles are not exactly the same, these constraints are independent and reduce the number of free cells by exactly r*c, no matter how the rectangles overlap. Overlap only creates edges that connect two cells already within the first rectangle, but this does not change the total number of independent equivalence classes; the count remains n*m - r*c. The special case dx = 0 and dy = 0 produces self‑loops, which do not reduce the number of degrees of freedom, yielding exponent n*m. Adding the overlap term therefore inflates the exponent and the resulting answer, as demonstrated by the first sample (64 instead of 32)."
    }
